'''Ueno Ōji''' (上野王子) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Gobo|ja|御坊市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Wakayama Prefecture|ja|和歌山県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Japan. It is one of the {{ill|Kujūku Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|qq=draft|qq=draft}} shrines. The site of the shrine is marked with a sign for Ueno Ōji at the outskirts of the Ueno settlement in Nata-chō, just before the bridge crossing the Uenogawa River along the old road near [[:en:Japan_National_Route_42|Japan National Route 42]]. It was designated as a Gobo City Historic Site on May 8, 1969.<ref>{{Cite web
| publisher=Gobo City Board of Education
| url=http://www.city.gobo.wakayama.jp/gobo/1120ka/bunkazai/20.html
| title=Site of Ueno Ōji
| accessdate=2009-09-27
}}</ref>

== History ==

While the exact founding date of Ueno Ōji is unknown, it appears in historical records dating back to the early 12th century. In the {{ill|Chūyūki|ja|中右記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, an entry dated October 20, 1109 (Tennin 2) mentions a purification ritual performed at Ueno Slope. The shrine is first explicitly mentioned as "Next, Ueno Ōji" in an entry from October 10, 1201 (Kennin 1) in the "Kumano Dō no Aimagoki" (included in the {{ill|Meigetsuki|ja|明月記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). Another record of a pilgrimage visit appears in the {{ill|Minkeiki|ja|民経記|qq=draft|qq=draft}} dated April 26, 1210 (Jōgen 4).<ref name="Heibon_1997_105">Heibonsha [1997: 105]</ref>

In early modern records, it is noted that a Buddhist well (仏井戸) located along the Oguri Kaidō within a field was considered the original site of the shrine (as mentioned in the {{ill|Kiizoku Fudoki|ja|紀伊続風土記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). Three Buddhist statues—{{ill|Jizō Bosatsu|ja|地蔵菩薩|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Amitābha|ja|阿弥陀如来|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Kannon|ja|観音菩薩|1=Guanyin|2=ja|3=観音菩薩|lt=Kannon Bodhisattva|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<ref name="Nishi_1987_129">Nishi [1987: 129]</ref>—located at the bottom of the well are believed to be the honji (本地仏) of the shrine. Pilgrims frequently visited this site, as noted in the {{ill|Kii Meisho Zue|ja|紀伊名所図会|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The Buddhist well still exists along the national road, and it is traditionally cleaned twice a year.<ref name="Nishi_1987_129"/>

The Buddhist well was also designated as a Gobo City Historic Site on July 18, 1969.<ref>{{Cite web
| publisher=Gobo City Board of Education
| url=http://www.city.gobo.wakayama.jp/gobo/1120ka/bunkazai/21.html
| title=Buddhist Well
| accessdate=2009-09-27
}}</ref>

