'''Ueno Ōji''' (上野王子) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Gobō, Wakayama|en|Gobō, Wakayama|WD=Q847572|lt=Gobo|1=Gobō, Wakayama}}, {{ill|Wakayama Prefecture|en|Wakayama Prefecture|WD=Q131314|lt=Wakayama Prefecture|1=Wakayama Prefecture}}, Japan. It is one of the {{ill|Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}} shrines. The site of the shrine is marked with a sign for Ueno Ōji at the outskirts of the Ueno settlement in Nata-chō, just before the bridge crossing the Uenogawa River along the old road near {{ill|Japan_National_Route_42|en|Japan_National_Route_42|WD=Q2003243|lt=Japan National Route 42|1=Japan National Route 42}}. It was designated as a Gobo City Historic Site on May 8, 1969.<ref>{{Cite web
| publisher=Gobo City Board of Education
| url=http://www.city.gobo.wakayama.jp/gobo/1120ka/bunkazai/20.html
| title=Site of Ueno Ōji
| accessdate=2009-09-27
}}</ref>

== History ==

While the exact founding date of Ueno Ōji is unknown, it appears in historical records dating back to the early 12th century. In the {{ill|Chūyūki|ja|中右記|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chūyūki|qq=}}, an entry dated October 20, 1109 (Tennin 2) mentions a purification ritual performed at Ueno Slope. The shrine is first explicitly mentioned as "Next, Ueno Ōji" in an entry from October 10, 1201 (Kennin 1) in the "Kumano Dō no Aimagoki" (included in the {{ill|Meigetsuki|ja|明月記|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meigetsuki|qq=}}). Another record of a pilgrimage visit appears in the {{ill|Minkeiki|ja|民経記|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minkeiki|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 広橋経光|1=Hirohashi Tsunemitsu|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q20042592}} dated April 26, 1210 (Jōgen 4).<ref name="Heibon_1997_105">Heibonsha [1997: 105]</ref>

In early modern records, it is noted that a Buddhist well (仏井戸) located along the Oguri Kaidō within a field was considered the original site of the shrine (as mentioned in the {{ill|Kiizoku Fudoki|ja|紀伊続風土記|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiizoku Fudoki|1=Kii Zoku Fudoki|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11604964}}). Three Buddhist statues—{{ill|Kṣitigarbha|en|Kṣitigarbha|WD=Q604687|lt=Jizō Bosatsu|1=Kṣitigarbha}}, {{ill|Amitābha|en|Amitābha|WD=Q236242|lt=Amitābha|1=Amitābha}}, and {{ill|Avalokiteśvara|en|Avalokiteśvara|WD=Q193849|lt=Kannon Bodhisattva|1=Avalokiteśvara}}<ref name="Nishi_1987_129">Nishi [1987: 129]</ref>—located at the bottom of the well are believed to be the honji (本地仏) of the shrine. Pilgrims frequently visited this site, as noted in the {{ill|Kii Meisho Zue|ja|紀伊名所図会|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kii Meisho Zue|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. The Buddhist well still exists along the national road, and it is traditionally cleaned twice a year.<ref name="Nishi_1987_129"/>

The Buddhist well was also designated as a Gobo City Historic Site on July 18, 1969.<ref>{{Cite web
| publisher=Gobo City Board of Education
| url=http://www.city.gobo.wakayama.jp/gobo/1120ka/bunkazai/21.html
| title=Buddhist Well
| accessdate=2009-09-27
}}</ref>

